## The Week at a Glance

- 🔴 **High — Exchange Server vulnerability requires immediate patching.** A June 2026 security update addresses a confirmed vulnerability in Exchange Server (CVE-2026-42897) that could allow attackers to execute malicious code through Outlook Web Access. Organizations running on-premises Exchange must act now.
- 🔴 **High — Entra ID authentication policy changes are enforced by end of 2026.** Microsoft is retiring legacy authentication controls and requiring migration of custom MFA configurations. Organizations that delay risk losing consistent security policy enforcement across their workforce.
- 🟡 **Medium — Exchange ActiveSync certificate-based authentication retires by end of 2026.** Mobile email clients using direct certificate authentication to Exchange Online must be reconfigured through Entra ID. New tenants are blocked immediately; existing tenants have until year-end.
- 🟢 **Low — AI capabilities are accelerating rapidly across Microsoft 365.** New AI agents, models (GPT-5.5 Instant, Claude Opus 4.8, Claude Fable 5), and agentic governance tools are now generally available. No immediate action required, but these shape your AI strategy and licensing planning for the second half of 2026.

*Sources: [Exchange Team Blog — June 2026 Security Updates](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/released-june-2026-exchange-server-security-updates/ba-p/4524491) · [Entra ID Security Updates Blog](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/microsoft-entra-id-security-updates-what-organizations-need-to/ba-p/4522024) · [Exchange ActiveSync CBA Retirement](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/retirement-of-direct-exchange-activesync-certificate-based/ba-p/4517896)*

---

## Why This Week Matters

Microsoft's on-premises Exchange vulnerability and the Entra ID authentication enforcement timeline represent two different flavors of the same underlying risk: organizations that have deferred infrastructure modernization are now facing hard deadlines with measurable security consequences. Simultaneously, Microsoft is placing big bets on AI agents becoming operational infrastructure — not just productivity tools — which means governance, data security, and licensing decisions made in the next 90 days will define your AI risk posture for the coming year.

The one thing leadership must understand: **deferring patching and identity modernization while simultaneously adopting AI agents creates compounding risk** — attackers are already using AI to accelerate phishing and credential theft, and a vulnerable email server or bypassed MFA policy is exactly the gap they exploit.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog — AI Brands as Bait](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/06/08/ai-brands-as-bait-how-threat-actors-are-using-the-ai-hype-in-social-engineering/) · [Entra ID Security Updates Blog](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/microsoft-entra-id-security-updates-what-organizations-need-to/ba-p/4522024)*

