## What Your Employees Will Notice

- **Teams is faster and more responsive.** Microsoft has shipped significant performance improvements to Teams, meaning quicker load times, faster message delivery, and more reliable calls. Users who have complained about Teams being slow may notice a meaningful difference.
- **Copilot looks different.** The Microsoft 365 Copilot app has a redesigned interface — cleaner and more integrated across Word, Excel, PowerPoint, and Teams. Expect questions from users unfamiliar with the new layout.
- **New AI models available in Copilot.** Users with Microsoft 365 Copilot licenses will see options to use newer AI models including GPT-5.5 Instant and Claude Opus 4.8. Some users may ask what the differences are between models.
- **Copilot can now answer and schedule follow-ups for Teams calls.** Through the new "call delegation" feature (available via Frontier program), Copilot can screen incoming calls and schedule follow-ups on a user's behalf. This is opt-in and may generate questions about privacy and what Copilot is "doing" with calls.
- **Teams Phone users can now have up to 10 phone numbers.** Users who need to represent multiple lines of business in Teams Phone no longer need separate accounts or workarounds.
- **Office location auto-updates via Wi-Fi.** Employees who opt in will have their workplace location in Teams and Microsoft Places updated automatically when they connect to a company Wi-Fi network — no manual check-in required.
- **Windows Do Not Disturb now pauses Teams notifications.** When employees enable Windows Do Not Disturb, Teams notifications will automatically pause. This may reduce help desk tickets about unwanted interruptions but could also cause some users to miss messages.
- **Copilot Notebooks now available to more users.** Previously restricted to full Microsoft 365 Copilot subscribers, Copilot Notebooks is rolling out to Copilot Chat users — a broader population may now be able to collaborate in AI-powered shared notebooks.

*Sources: [Teams Blog — Making Teams More Responsive](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-teams-blog/making-microsoft-teams-more-responsive-reliable-and-ready-for/ba-p/4526527) · [What's New in Microsoft 365 Copilot — May 2026](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-365-copilot-blog/what-s-new-in-microsoft-365-copilot-may-2026/ba-p/4522010) · [Copilot Notebooks June 2026](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-365-copilot-blog/what-s-new-in-notebooks-june-2026/ba-p/4525625)*

---

## What Your Help Desk Should Expect

- **"Why does Copilot look different?"** The redesigned Copilot interface will prompt a wave of "what happened to Copilot?" tickets. Prepare a brief communication in advance of the change reaching your users.
- **"I'm not getting Teams notifications."** The new Windows Do Not Disturb integration may confuse users who unintentionally enabled DND and can't figure out why Teams has gone quiet.
- **"I can't send email from my phone anymore."** If any users are on legacy mobile mail clients using certificate-based authentication to Exchange Online, they may begin experiencing failures. Help desk staff should be briefed on the EAS CBA retirement.
- **"My email client can't connect / I'm getting TLS errors."** Legacy POP3/IMAP4 clients using TLS 1.0 or 1.1 will lose connectivity as deprecation takes effect. Identify affected users proactively before this becomes a ticket storm.
- **Copilot call delegation confusion.** Users enrolled in the Frontier program who enable Copilot call delegation may generate tickets asking what happened to their missed calls or why Copilot responded on their behalf.
- **Exchange Server patching-related downtime.** If your organization applies the June Exchange security update, brief the help desk on expected maintenance windows and potential short-term mail flow disruptions.
- **New model choices in Copilot.** Power users will ask which model to use, whether model selection affects data privacy, and how to switch between models.

*Sources: [What's New in Teams — May 2026](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-teams-blog/what-s-new-in-microsoft-teams-may-2026-build-edition/ba-p/4524613) · [Exchange Team Blog — EAS CBA Retirement](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/retirement-of-direct-exchange-activesync-certificate-based/ba-p/4517896) · [Exchange Team Blog — Legacy TLS Deprecation](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/deprecating-legacy-tls-and-endpoints-for-pop-and-imap-in/ba-p/4515201)*

