## If You Take No Action

**Exchange Server CVE-2026-42897 remains unpatched:** An attacker can send a specially crafted email to any user with access to Outlook Web Access. If the user opens that email, the attacker can execute arbitrary code in the browser context — potentially harvesting credentials, installing malware, or pivoting to internal systems. This vulnerability is publicly disclosed, meaning the attack window is actively shortening. Cyber insurance carriers increasingly deny claims where known, patchable vulnerabilities were left unaddressed.

**Entra ID legacy MFA migration is not completed:** When Microsoft enforces retirement of custom MFA controls and legacy Conditional Access patterns, security policies you believe are protecting your organization will stop applying uniformly. Attackers who have already mapped your authentication flows may find gaps that did not exist before. For organizations under CMMC, SOC 2, or cyber insurance requirements mandating MFA coverage, this could create audit findings or policy violations at the moment Microsoft enforces the change — leaving no runway to remediate before consequences arrive.

**Exchange ActiveSync certificate-based authentication is not remediated:** At year-end, mobile users and automated systems relying on direct certificate authentication to Exchange Online will lose email access without warning. In environments where field workers, executives, or automated notification systems depend on mobile email, this creates operational disruption that is entirely preventable with planning started now.

*Sources: [Exchange Team Blog — Addressing CVE-2026-42897](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/addressing-exchange-server-may-2026-vulnerability-cve-2026-42897/ba-p/4518498) · [Entra ID Security Updates Blog](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/microsoft-entra-id-security-updates-what-organizations-need-to/ba-p/4522024) · [Exchange ActiveSync CBA Retirement](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/exchange-team-blog/retirement-of-direct-exchange-activesync-certificate-based/ba-p/4517896)*